snippet.textDisplay:
Roz is entitled to his opinion, but I couldn't disagree more. As a long time Star Wars fan who loved TLJ - it might even be my favourite stand-alone film in the franchise - and TFA, I really didn't like Episode IX. It's a mess which short-changes every character except Kylo, and whose plot is essentially "find the thing which will help us find the thing which will help us find the thing" and is essentially nonsensical from start to finish. In much the same way as Episode III made me re-evaluate the prequels in a more positive light, this film has forced me to re-evaluate the sequels in a more negative light, and that's not a position I wanted to be in.

I think on the one hand, you have to blame Johnson for for taking the franchise in an (admittedly awesome) direction which clearly wasn't what Abrams thought he was setting up or was willing to buy in to. On the other, you have to blame Abrams for wasting so much time retconning TLJ rather than finding a way to make a satisfying conclusion. But, in the end you have to blame Disney. Either they should have laid down a road map which different directors would follow right from the start, or they shouldn't have chickened out on having Johnson write the third film. The way they handled this was the worst of all worlds.

TLJ made me think star wars was dead forever but JJ course corrected enough and even utilized some of RJ's stuff.  I appreciated the urgent pacing of the movie because I think star wars needed an urgent fix; meaning lets go and fix this shit right away and connect these movies.  Good. Fine. Honestly wish JJ did all three movies and that TLJ never happened.

snippet.textDisplay: I was a huge fan of the original movies, including the not so popular prequels (in spite of their undeniable flaws). Unfortunately "in terms of story", I fail to find anything enjoyable or satisfying in the Disney trilogy. As an old school fan, there complete lack of respect for the original trilogy infuriates me. The fact that they try to pander to the fan base, while simultaneously disrespecting the origins makes it even worse. Thankfully this same group managed to produce a couple of gems in "Rogue One", and "The Mandalorian". This is the only thing that gives me any hope for the future of the franchise.

snippet.textDisplay: This new DiSNEY©'s Star Wars™ product is a sugar-coated soulless factory made item, stuffed and tasteless, full of lensflares and ...stuff. Fast paced and boring was also my reaction during the screening. It carries so many inconsistencies that the old suspension of disbelief every human shares when told a story, was on hold too many times. I did like some of the comedy moments, specifically C3-PO's lines. But that's not much and the overall writing is still so incredibly dumb, it feels like it's coming from the feverish mind of a 12 years old fanboy, who wanted to compress 2 movies material into a single show. Or is it a TV pilot? Ah, well. The Force Awakens was already the worst thing happening in this universe far away now deserted by those who liked it the most; worse than The Phantom Menace but better than the Holiday Special. Thanks JJ Abrams! You did it again.

JJ Abrams started the trilogy with baking a generic cake with expensive ingredients only to have Rian Johnson come in declaring said cake to be a peanut butter and jelly sandwich. Force Awakens will always be the best but each subsequent movie just becomes more disjointed and confusing then the former. snippet.textDisplay: OMG!!! Wait wait wait.....you're telling me these three movies were a starwars trilogy?!!! F me! this whole time I thought I was watching the continuing saga of SPACE BALLS. Well if you liked the movie I guess some people are more easily thrilled than others. kinda like seeing a back flip. most people who can't do one would be impressed. but when you attach the name Starwars to something, you have just entered the Olympic hall of fame and at this level a simple backflip won't win you a metal in this arena, so if you enjoyed it.....congrats, you have just promoted to a "NORMIE" aka Fast food TV dinner quality fan fare.

snippet.textDisplay: I would describe it as follows: People were excited to get some new adventures which builds on the lore. TFA did not quite succeed at this. So in the TLJ your expectationsa nd views are challenged. It wasn't in a rude way. TLJ looked at the building blocks that were provided by TFA and built ontop of those instead to stick to them. But people seem to have no idea what they actually want and now we are here where TROS does not build on TLJ in  a new but just replaces the things TLJ achieved. Which is a bummer.
